            <p></p>
            
            <li><strong>Gudi Padwa:</strong> The Marathi New Year, celebrated with traditional rituals and feasts.</li>
            <p>
                Gudi Padwa, celebrated as the Marathi New Year, holds special significance in Konkan. The festival typically falls in March or April and marks the arrival of spring. Families prepare by cleaning and decorating their homes, often creating intricate rangoli designs at their entrances. Central to the celebrations is the Gudi itself—a colorful silk cloth tied to a bamboo pole, adorned with a garland of flowers and a brass pot on top, symbolizing prosperity and good fortune. People gather to perform rituals, offer prayers, and enjoy traditional dishes like puran poli and shrikhand. The day also features processions, folk music, and dance, bringing communities together in joyous celebration. Gudi Padwa not only marks a new beginning but also reinforces cultural ties and family bonds, making it a cherished occasion in Konkan.
            </p>
