    <section>
        <h2><u>Art </u>& <u> Craft </u></h2>
        
        <p>The Konkan region is also known for its traditional art forms, including:</p>
    </section>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Warli Art:</strong> Vibrant wall paintings often depicting mythological themes.</li>
        <p>Warli painting is a traditional tribal art form originating from the Warli tribe in Maharashtra, particularly in the Konkan region. Characterized by its simple, monochromatic designs, this art uses white pigment made from rice paste on mud walls, creating striking contrast against earthy backgrounds. The motifs often depict everyday life, nature, and social rituals, showcasing scenes of farming, dancing, and wildlife.</p>
        <p>Warli art is deeply connected to the tribe's cultural beliefs, often incorporating symbols that represent fertility and community. The geometric shapes—circles, triangles, and squares—are fundamental to the style, symbolizing harmony and the interconnectedness of life. Traditionally passed down through generations, Warli painting has gained popularity beyond tribal communities and is now featured in contemporary art and home decor. This unique art form not only preserves the rich heritage of the Warli tribe but also serves as a visual narrative of their lifestyle and environment, captivating audiences worldwide.</p>
